<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> leave someone cold • leave someone out in the cold</xh5><p> <i>leave someone cold—</i>fail to impress or interest a person: An orator may discourse very eloquently on injustice and <u>leave his audience cold</u>.</p><p> <i>leave someone out in the cold—</i>ignore or abandon smb.: Developing countries might be <u>left out in the cold</u> in current world trade talks.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not fully correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>leave someone out</b>—1. <i>= leave someone out in the cold: </i>It’s Mary’s own fault if she feels <u>left out</u> at the party; she makes no effort to be friendly to people. 2. <i>fail to include a person (in a list, etc.): </i>He toasted all the other ladies present, but <u>left Jane out</u>.</p> </entry>
